-[non-english speech]

273
00:11:48,537 --> 00:11:50,604
CHAMBER: This fleet is
extremely inefficient.

274
00:11:50,704 --> 00:11:52,237
The command structure
and child rearing

275
00:11:52,337 --> 00:11:54,670
are both defective, while
the citizenry's behavior

276
00:11:54,770 --> 00:11:57,337
is disorganized.

277
00:11:57,437 --> 00:11:59,570
And I cannot comprehend
why you care for the weak.

278
00:12:03,270 --> 00:12:04,670
-Disorganized eh?

279
00:12:04,770 --> 00:12:08,104
So that's how we look to
a visitor from the stars.

280
00:12:08,204 --> 00:12:10,270
Pardon me but I beg to differ.

281
00:12:10,370 --> 00:12:13,704
This efficiency you speak of
has a rather narrow scope.

282
00:12:13,804 --> 00:12:15,504
I have an idea.

283
00:12:15,604 --> 00:12:19,004
I think it's time that you
met Amy's brother, Bebel.

284
00:12:19,104 --> 00:12:20,337
-[non-english speech]

285
00:12:20,437 --> 00:12:22,604
CHAMBER: Will I be able to
attain any useful information

286
00:12:22,704 --> 00:12:25,437
by engaging in discourse
with that person?

287
00:12:25,537 --> 00:12:28,204
-Whether or not it's useful
is entirely up to you.

288
00:12:42,951 --> 00:12:43,984
AMY: I see.

289
00:12:44,084 --> 00:12:49,784
So even Doctor Oldham
didn't know Bebel.

290
00:12:49,884 --> 00:12:51,418
I'm home.

291
00:12:51,518 --> 00:12:52,084
BEBEL: Hey sis.

292
00:12:52,184 --> 00:12:52,918
Welcome back.

293
00:13:00,218 --> 00:13:01,551
-Uh.

294
00:13:01,651 --> 00:13:03,018
-Ah.

295
00:13:03,118 --> 00:13:04,751
Hey, is that Ledo?

296
00:13:04,851 --> 00:13:05,851
Wow.

297
00:13:05,951 --> 00:13:07,651
He really is your friend
just like you said.

298
00:13:07,751 --> 00:13:08,584
-Heh heh.

299
00:13:08,684 --> 00:13:10,751
-You're awesome sis.

300
00:13:10,851 --> 00:13:11,884
I'm Bebel.

301
00:13:11,984 --> 00:13:14,018
It's nice to meet you.

302
00:13:14,118 --> 00:13:16,984
-Nice to meet you.

303
00:13:17,084 --> 00:13:18,951
LEDO (VOICEOVER): This
is Amy's little brother?

304
00:13:21,651 --> 00:13:23,818
-Please come and sit down.

305
00:13:23,918 --> 00:13:26,551
-Ledo asked to come here
so that he can meet you.

306
00:13:26,651 --> 00:13:27,984
-He did, really?

307
00:13:28,084 --> 00:13:30,751
LEDO: Correct.

308
00:13:30,851 --> 00:13:31,884
[non-english speech]

309
00:13:31,984 --> 00:13:33,418
CHAMBER: I would like
to request information

310
00:13:33,518 --> 00:13:34,784
regarding this place.

311
00:13:34,884 --> 00:13:35,818
BEBEL: Wait, that voice.

312
00:13:35,918 --> 00:13:36,418
Was that?

313
00:13:36,518 --> 00:13:37,484
-Yep that's right.

314
00:13:37,584 --> 00:13:39,218
This is Chamber's
communication module.

315
00:13:39,318 --> 00:13:40,184
-Awesome.

316
00:13:40,284 --> 00:13:42,084
So a machine really can talk.

317
00:13:42,184 --> 00:13:43,951
Uh, Mr. Chamber?

318
00:13:44,051 --> 00:13:45,218
-Designation Chamber.

319
00:13:45,318 --> 00:13:48,518
I'm an artificial intelligence
created to aid my pilot.

320
00:13:48,618 --> 00:13:49,951
-Remarkable.

321
00:13:50,051 --> 00:13:52,918
And you understand
Earth language so well.

322
00:13:53,018 --> 00:13:53,951
SAAYA: Amy, are you home.

323
00:13:54,051 --> 00:13:55,418
MELTY: We're
totally shorthanded.

324
00:13:55,518 --> 00:13:57,918
Help us or--

325
00:13:58,018 --> 00:13:59,951
SAAYA: Uh, the hottie?

326
00:14:00,051 --> 00:14:01,518
MELTY: Didn't waste
any time, did ya?

327
00:14:01,618 --> 00:14:03,751
-It's not like that at all.

328
00:14:03,851 --> 00:14:06,384
Sorry, I've got more work to do.

329
00:14:06,484 --> 00:14:07,851
BEBEL: Be safe sis.

330
00:14:07,951 --> 00:14:09,684
-Man, just when it
was getting good too.

331
00:14:09,784 --> 00:14:11,718
MELTY: Oooo, just when
what was getting good?

332
00:14:11,818 --> 00:14:14,084
AMY: I told you it's
nothing like that.

333
00:14:14,184 --> 00:14:15,484
Bebel, take care of Ledo, OK.

334
00:14:15,584 --> 00:14:16,451
-Bye Amy.

335
00:14:16,551 --> 00:14:17,684
Don't rush too much
or you'll trip.

336
00:14:17,784 --> 00:14:18,984
AMY: I know-- [person stumbling]

337
00:14:19,084 --> 00:14:20,118
SAAYA: Amy, you have to--

338
00:14:20,218 --> 00:14:20,918
-Sorry.

339
00:14:21,018 --> 00:14:23,184
Amy's so hyper.

340
00:14:23,284 --> 00:14:24,551
-I do not mind.

341
00:14:24,651 --> 00:14:25,584
-Is it true?

342
00:14:25,684 --> 00:14:28,784
Are you really from
outer space Ledo?

343
00:14:28,884 --> 00:14:31,251
Oh, I've always wondered
what's up there.

344
00:14:31,351 --> 00:14:33,184
What is life like in space.

345
00:14:33,284 --> 00:14:35,184
I'm real curious
to know about it.

346
00:14:35,284 --> 00:14:36,284
LEDO: [non-english speech]

347
00:14:36,384 --> 00:14:37,684
CHAMBER: In the
Galactic Alliance,

348
00:14:37,784 --> 00:14:40,784
the primary mission is to seek
out and destroy the Hideauze.

349
00:14:40,884 --> 00:14:42,784
-What are Hideauze?

350
00:14:42,884 --> 00:14:44,484
-[non-english speech]

351
00:14:44,584 --> 00:14:46,218
CHAMBER: An alien life
form that threatens

352
00:14:46,318 --> 00:14:47,951
the existence of humanity.

353
00:14:48,051 --> 00:14:50,784
BEBEL: Have you always
fought with them?

354
00:14:50,884 --> 00:14:51,651
-[non-english speech]

355
00:14:51,751 --> 00:14:53,251
CHAMBER: The war
has been ongoing

356
00:14:53,351 --> 00:14:56,751
since the initial formation
of the Galactic Alliance

357
00:14:56,851 --> 00:14:58,751
BEBEL: Wow.

358
00:14:58,851 --> 00:15:02,051
That sounds very different
from how life is here.

359
00:15:02,151 --> 00:15:03,684
Do you ever get tired of war?

360
00:15:03,784 --> 00:15:05,051
-[non-english speech]

361
00:15:05,151 --> 00:15:09,551
CHAMBER: For battle fatigue,
there is no recourse but death.

362
00:15:09,651 --> 00:15:12,384
-Warfare or death.

363
00:15:12,484 --> 00:15:15,684
That's a rough choice.

364
00:15:15,784 --> 00:15:16,518
What about here?

365
00:15:16,618 --> 00:15:19,451
Have you settle in?

366
00:15:19,551 --> 00:15:21,418
-[non-english speech]

367
00:15:21,518 --> 00:15:24,084
CHAMBER: I cannot make sense
of the organizational structure

368
00:15:24,184 --> 00:15:25,484
of Gargantia.

369
00:15:25,584 --> 00:15:27,151
-Why not?

370
00:15:27,251 --> 00:15:28,518
-[non-english speech]

371
00:15:28,618 --> 00:15:30,784
CHAMBER: I'm unable to discern
the reason for running such

372
00:15:30,884 --> 00:15:33,051
an inefficient and
useless operation.

373
00:15:33,151 --> 00:15:36,084
-This fleet isn't a
military operation.

374
00:15:36,184 --> 00:15:38,818
It's just everyone coming
together to survive.

375
00:15:38,918 --> 00:15:41,384
Sometimes we help each other,
and other times we fight.

376
00:15:41,484 --> 00:15:42,584
It's how we coexist.

377
00:15:42,684 --> 00:15:44,451
There is no set plan.

378
00:15:44,551 --> 00:15:45,418
-[non-english speech]

379
00:15:45,518 --> 00:15:46,051
CHAMBER: Query.

380
00:15:46,151 --> 00:15:47,384
Why is that?

381
00:15:47,484 --> 00:15:49,751
-So that everyone is free
to live their own lives.

382
00:15:49,851 --> 00:15:51,618
That's what's important.

383
00:15:51,718 --> 00:15:52,951
-[non-english speech]

384
00:15:53,051 --> 00:15:54,518
CHAMBER: The answer is unclear.

385
00:15:54,618 --> 00:15:56,851
The behavioral objective
of the human race

386
00:15:56,951 --> 00:15:59,651
is subjugating the
enemy, the Hideauze.

387
00:15:59,751 --> 00:16:02,484
Without that purpose, the human
race cannot sustain stable

388
00:16:02,584 --> 00:16:03,284
development.

389
00:16:03,384 --> 00:16:04,551
-Really?

390
00:16:04,651 --> 00:16:05,618
LEDO: [non-english speech]

391
00:16:05,718 --> 00:16:06,884
CHAMBER: In the
Galactic Alliance,

392
00:16:06,984 --> 00:16:09,084
humans that do not further
the behavioral objective

393
00:16:09,184 --> 00:16:10,451
are culled immediately.

394
00:16:10,551 --> 00:16:13,318
-They're culled?

395
00:16:13,418 --> 00:16:14,451
But wait.

396
00:16:14,551 --> 00:16:16,618
What happens when the
Hideauze are defeated?

397
00:16:16,718 --> 00:16:19,684
What would the Galactic
Alliance do then?

398
00:16:19,784 --> 00:16:21,984
What would you do Ledo?

399
00:16:22,084 --> 00:16:22,884
-[non-english speech]

400
00:16:22,984 --> 00:16:24,251
CHAMBER: I would
stand by until I

401
00:16:24,351 --> 00:16:25,984
received further instructions.

402
00:16:26,084 --> 00:16:29,451
-And what would you do if
those instructions never came?

403
00:16:29,551 --> 00:16:30,684
-[non-english speech]

404
00:16:30,784 --> 00:16:34,118
CHAMBER: I would just
continue to stand by.

405
00:16:34,218 --> 00:16:37,084
-Then we're not so very
different after all.

406
00:16:37,184 --> 00:16:39,218
-We are not different?

407
00:16:39,318 --> 00:16:40,584
-Mhm.

408
00:16:40,684 --> 00:16:43,384
Standing by, you'd have to go
on living to do that, right?

409
00:16:51,118 --> 00:16:52,418
-Ledo.

410
00:16:52,518 --> 00:16:55,284
I heard Joe went and
commandeered your yunburo.

411
00:16:55,384 --> 00:16:57,584
A shame to see the dashing
hero on the sidelines.

412
00:17:00,584 --> 00:17:01,651
Ledo?

413
00:17:01,751 --> 00:17:02,618
[non-english speech]

414
00:17:02,718 --> 00:17:03,651
CHAMBER: Query.

415
00:17:03,751 --> 00:17:05,284
Are my actions in
any way beneficial?

416
00:17:05,384 --> 00:17:08,618
-Of course.

417
00:17:08,718 --> 00:17:11,984
Did you forget how you saved
us from the pirates twice?

418
00:17:12,084 --> 00:17:13,318
-[non-english speech]

419
00:17:13,418 --> 00:17:15,151
CHAMBER: Right now
I have no function.

420
00:17:15,251 --> 00:17:17,684
All I do is observe Chamber.

421
00:17:17,784 --> 00:17:19,951
-You're just not
used to it here.

422
00:17:20,051 --> 00:17:21,051
LEDO: [non-english speech]

423
00:17:21,151 --> 00:17:22,418
CHAMBER: I am
unable to determine

424
00:17:22,518 --> 00:17:24,518
my most appropriate
course of action.

425
00:17:24,618 --> 00:17:26,784
-Most appropriate
course of action?

426
00:17:26,884 --> 00:17:28,818
You know, you've got a
knock off this soldier boy

427
00:17:28,918 --> 00:17:31,784
mentality you've got going on.

428
00:17:31,884 --> 00:17:33,084
-Knock off?

429
00:17:33,184 --> 00:17:34,084
-Yeah.

430
00:17:34,184 --> 00:17:35,284
And try to loosen
up and have fun--

431
00:17:40,651 --> 00:17:42,051
-What is this?

432
00:17:42,151 --> 00:17:42,818
What is happening?

433
00:17:42,918 --> 00:17:44,051
CHAMBER: Weather phenomenon.

434
00:17:44,151 --> 00:17:45,218
It is not toxic.

435
00:17:45,318 --> 00:17:45,851
-Come on.

436
00:17:45,951 --> 00:17:46,951
We gotta hurry up.

437
00:17:47,051 --> 00:17:49,484
Get your yunburo and
help us gather the rain.

438
00:17:49,584 --> 00:17:51,184
Fresh water is vital.

439
00:17:51,284 --> 00:17:52,351
-Want should do?

440
00:17:52,451 --> 00:17:53,618
-There's a tarp over there.

441
00:17:53,718 --> 00:17:56,418
Spread it out and collect
all the rain you can.

442
00:17:56,518 --> 00:17:58,251
-Chamber.

443
00:17:58,351 --> 00:17:58,792
-Roger.

444
00:18:38,318 --> 00:18:38,784
-Right.

445
00:18:38,884 --> 00:18:39,718
Nice and easy.

446
00:18:42,584 --> 00:18:46,151
CHAMBER: I detect variations
in your brain waves.

447
00:18:46,251 --> 00:18:49,284
-I was wondering about the war
and how it was progressing.

448
00:18:49,384 --> 00:18:52,784
-Given the circumstances, such
consideration is fruitless

449
00:18:52,884 --> 00:18:54,018
-I'm aware of that.

450
00:18:54,118 --> 00:18:55,951
-Hottie spotted 1 o'clock.

451
00:18:56,051 --> 00:18:58,184
He is just so darn cute.

452
00:18:58,284 --> 00:18:59,584
-I feel bad.

453
00:18:59,684 --> 00:19:01,684
He's a stranger in
a strange place.

454
00:19:01,784 --> 00:19:04,484
Plus he's alone without
any friends or family.

455
00:19:04,584 --> 00:19:05,318
MELTY: Don't worry.

456
00:19:05,418 --> 00:19:07,951
I'm sure he'll be fine, right?

457
00:19:08,051 --> 00:19:08,951
-Huh?

458
00:19:09,051 --> 00:19:10,118
You're concerned about him.

459
00:19:10,218 --> 00:19:11,118
I can tell.

460
00:19:11,218 --> 00:19:12,618
Go on, get over there.

461
00:19:15,684 --> 00:19:17,084
-Ledo.

462
00:19:17,184 --> 00:19:18,751
You know you're soaked, right?

463
00:19:18,851 --> 00:19:20,551
You'll get sick like that.

464
00:19:20,651 --> 00:19:22,118
Come dry off at my place.

465
00:19:25,484 --> 00:19:27,918
BEBEL: Looks like
it was some squall.

466
00:19:28,018 --> 00:19:29,484
CHAMBER: That was
my first observation

467
00:19:29,584 --> 00:19:32,551
of concentrated precipitation.

468
00:19:32,651 --> 00:19:34,418
BEBEL: Is there
rain in space too?

469
00:19:34,518 --> 00:19:35,118
-No.

470
00:19:35,218 --> 00:19:36,084
BEBEL: Are there oceans?

471
00:19:36,184 --> 00:19:38,118
-No.

472
00:19:38,218 --> 00:19:41,118
-What about sickly
people like me?

473
00:19:41,218 --> 00:19:43,818
CHAMBER: They do not exist.

474
00:19:43,918 --> 00:19:45,451
-You know what?

475
00:19:45,551 --> 00:19:51,018
I don't think of myself as
unnecessary because you see,

476
00:19:51,118 --> 00:19:53,151
I have my big sister.

477
00:19:53,251 --> 00:19:55,284
-Amy?

478
00:19:55,384 --> 00:19:56,384
-I love my big sister.

479
00:19:56,484 --> 00:19:57,718
And she needs me.

480
00:19:57,818 --> 00:19:59,418
And it's not just me.

481
00:19:59,518 --> 00:20:01,284
Someone must need you too Ledo.

482
00:20:01,384 --> 00:20:04,418
That's why you
survived and are here.

483
00:20:04,518 --> 00:20:05,884
-[non-english speech]

484
00:20:05,984 --> 00:20:07,551
CHAMBER: In the war
with the Hideauze,

485
00:20:07,651 --> 00:20:09,051
it is only necessary
for those who

486
00:20:09,151 --> 00:20:11,618
can be of service to survive.

487
00:20:11,718 --> 00:20:14,384
-Well, then what
about the opposite.

488
00:20:14,484 --> 00:20:17,451
Is there maybe someone out
there that you need Ledo?

489
00:20:17,551 --> 00:20:18,251
-Uh.

490
00:20:18,351 --> 00:20:19,584
-I need my big sister.

491
00:20:19,684 --> 00:20:21,651
But that's not the
most important thing.

492
00:20:21,751 --> 00:20:24,351
More than anything,
I'm here because I

493
00:20:24,451 --> 00:20:28,351
want to be here for my
big sister and myself.

494
00:20:28,451 --> 00:20:30,751
-But that is not--
[non-english speech]

495
00:20:30,851 --> 00:20:32,918
CHAMBER: To the Alliance,
that which is useless

496
00:20:33,018 --> 00:20:35,051
should not exist nor desire to.

497
00:20:35,151 --> 00:20:36,518
-If that's what
you truly believe,

498
00:20:36,618 --> 00:20:37,951
then why did you make this?

499
00:20:38,051 --> 00:20:40,384
-That is just--

500
00:20:40,484 --> 00:20:42,551
BEBEL: Sis told me you
made it but that you didn't

501
00:20:42,651 --> 00:20:45,384
know what it was or
what its use might be.

502
00:20:45,484 --> 00:20:48,718
I think it's some kind of flute.

503
00:20:48,818 --> 00:20:51,118
It's not necessary
for war at all.

504
00:20:51,218 --> 00:20:52,818
LEDO: A flute.

505
00:20:52,918 --> 00:20:53,851
-Mhm.

506
00:20:53,951 --> 00:20:55,784
Blowing air into it
produces a sound.

507
00:21:14,384 --> 00:21:15,151
-What's wrong?

508
00:21:15,251 --> 00:21:17,151
You're crying.

509
00:21:17,251 --> 00:21:20,184
Are you alright?

510
00:21:20,284 --> 00:21:21,018
-What is--

511
00:21:21,118 --> 00:21:21,884
-I'm so sorry.

512
00:21:21,984 --> 00:21:23,751
Did I say something wrong?

513
00:21:23,851 --> 00:21:28,818
-I do not know why--

514
00:21:28,918 --> 00:21:32,684
BEBEL: Perhaps you suddenly
remembered something sad.

515
00:21:32,784 --> 00:21:35,751
LEDO: Is that it?

516
00:21:35,851 --> 00:21:36,584
Bebel.

517
00:21:36,684 --> 00:21:37,284
BEBEL: Yes?

518
00:21:37,384 --> 00:21:37,984
-Please.

519
00:21:38,084 --> 00:21:40,051
I would like that again.

520
00:21:40,151 --> 00:21:40,592
-Of course.

521
00:21:48,351 --> 00:21:50,218
I made teas for you boys.

522
00:21:50,318 --> 00:21:51,718
It's Saaya's recommendation.

523
00:21:51,818 --> 00:21:53,184
She says it's good.

524
00:21:53,284 --> 00:21:54,184
Smells great.

525
00:22:00,218 --> 00:22:01,618
LEDO: Chamber,
what's your progress

526
00:22:01,718 --> 00:22:03,318
in finding our coordinates?

527
00:22:03,418 --> 00:22:05,118
-Lack of observational data.

528
00:22:05,218 --> 00:22:06,651
More time will be required.

529
00:22:06,751 --> 00:22:09,118
-I see.

530
00:22:09,218 --> 00:22:12,484
In that case, I'll need to
learn more about this planet.

531
00:22:12,584 --> 00:22:14,084
CHAMBER: That is unnecessary.

532
00:22:14,184 --> 00:22:18,084
Eventually you will return and
rejoin the main unit Ensign.

533
00:22:18,184 --> 00:22:19,284
-Yes.

534
00:22:19,384 --> 00:22:21,151
I know.

535
00:22:24,113 --> 00:22:27,246
[ending song]

